business names act 1980 (nt). the applicant and the respondents independently and simultaneously conceived and developed the idea of publishing a newspaper under the title of sunday territorian. the respondents published their first edition one week after the applicant. the applicant took proceedings under s 52 of the trade practices act 1974 (the act) and for passing off seeking injunctive and other relief and the respondents cross-claimed in similar terms.  held: (1) applying the required objective test, the use by the respondents of the same name as that already used by the applicants in circumstances where the respondents could not establish exclusive goodwill or reputation in the name, created potential for consumers to be misled as to the source of the respective products and therefore breached s 52 of the act.  global sportsman ltd v. mirror newspapers ltd (1984) atpr 45 ,339; bridges v. bridge stockbrokers ltd (federal court of australia, sheppard j, 18 july 1984, unreported), referred to with approval.  neyland v. toison holdings pty ltd (1983) 1 qd r 600 ; parkdale custom built furniture pty ltd v. puxu pty ltd [1982] hca 44 ; (1982) 149 clr 191 ; hornsby building information centre pty ltd v. sydney building information centre [1978] hca 11 ; (1978) 140 clr 216 ; motorcharge pty ltd v. motorcard pty ltd [1982] fca 90 ; (1982) 42 alr 136 ; 2 tpr 38 ; b m auto sales pty ltd v. budget rent-a-car system pty ltd (1976) 51 aljr 254 ; w h allen & co v. brown watson ltd (1965) rpc 191 ; the british broadcasting corporation v. talbot motor co ltd (1981) fsr 228 ; my kinda bones ltd v. dr pepper's stove co ltd (1984) fsr 289 , referred to.
